---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="What Is AuDHD? Autism + ADHD Together"
  description="AuDHD means having both autism and ADHD. Learn what the term means, how common the overlap is, and why the combination creates a unique experience."
  type="article"
>
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-12">
    <header class="mb-10">
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-text">What Is AuDHD?</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-text-light leading-relaxed">
        AuDHD is a community-coined term for having both autism and ADHD at the same time. Not autism <em>or</em> ADHD. Both, running simultaneously, often pulling you in opposite directions. Research suggests 30 to 50% of autistic people also have ADHD, which means this isn't a rare edge case. It's incredibly common.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="space-y-8">
      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Where the Term Comes From</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Until 2013, clinicians literally couldn't diagnose autism and ADHD together. The DSM (the manual used for psychiatric diagnoses in the US) treated them as mutually exclusive. If you had one, you didn't have the other. That changed with the DSM-5, which finally allowed dual diagnosis.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          But the medical world was slow to catch up. People living with both conditions needed language for their experience <em>now</em>, not whenever academia got around to it. So the neurodivergent community created "AuDHD" (a blend of "Au" from autism and "DHD" from ADHD). You'll see it across Reddit, TikTok, and online support communities. It's not a formal diagnostic label, but it describes something very real.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">How Common Is AuDHD?</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          More common than most people think. A 2019 meta-analysis published in <em>Neuroscience & Biobehavioral Reviews</em> found that roughly 50 to 70% of autistic individuals show clinically significant ADHD traits. Other studies put the co-occurrence rate between 30 and 50%. Either way, the overlap is substantial.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Here's the frustrating part: many people only get diagnosed with one. You might get an ADHD diagnosis in childhood because the hyperactivity is visible, while your autistic traits (need for routine, sensory sensitivities, social exhaustion) get overlooked. Or the reverse happens. An autism diagnosis comes first, and your attention difficulties get chalked up to "part of autism."
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">What Does AuDHD Actually Feel Like?</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Imagine your brain has two operating systems running at once. One craves structure, predictability, and sameness. The other craves novelty, spontaneity, and stimulation. They don't take turns. They run simultaneously.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          That creates experiences like:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-text-light leading-relaxed list-disc pl-6">
          <li><strong class="text-text">Building a detailed routine, then abandoning it within a week</strong> because the ADHD part of your brain rebels against monotony</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Hyperfocusing on a special interest for 14 hours</strong>, then suddenly losing all interest and feeling adrift</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Wanting deep social connection</strong> while simultaneously finding social interaction draining and confusing</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Being overwhelmed by sensory input</strong> but also actively seeking out intense sensory experiences (loud music, spicy food, weighted blankets)</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Starting a hundred creative projects</strong> with intense passion and finishing almost none of them</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          People often describe it as an internal tug-of-war. The autism wants to go deeper. The ADHD wants to move on. Neither side wins, and the person in the middle just feels stuck, confused, or exhausted.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Why Does It Matter to Know?</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Because strategies that work for autism alone or ADHD alone often fail for AuDHD. A rigid daily planner might help someone with ADHD, but for an AuDHD person, the autistic part loves it while the ADHD part can't stick with it. Body doubling works great for ADHD focus, but if your autistic sensory profile means another person's presence is distracting, it backfires.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Knowing you're AuDHD (or suspecting it) changes the game. You stop blaming yourself for failing at neurotypical strategies. You stop wondering why ADHD tips from influencers don't click. And you start building a toolkit that actually accounts for both sides of how your brain works.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Self-understanding isn't just nice to have. For a lot of AuDHD people, especially those diagnosed late, it's the difference between decades of shame and finally making sense of their own patterns.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Is AuDHD an Official Diagnosis?</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Not exactly. No clinician will write "AuDHD" on your diagnostic paperwork. What they <em>can</em> do (since 2013) is diagnose you with both Autism Spectrum Disorder and Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder. The term AuDHD is shorthand the community uses for that dual diagnosis. Think of it as a label people chose for themselves, which sometimes carries more meaning than the clinical version.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 bg-accent/10 rounded-[--radius-xl] p-6 sm:p-8">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-text mb-3">Explore More</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2">
        <li><a href="/quiz/is-it-audhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">Take the AuDHD Quiz &rarr;</a></li>
        <li><a href="/learn/signs-of-audhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">Common signs of AuDHD &rarr;</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
